keywords sealed names apparatus midgaard
---
The Sealed Names apparatus was Midgaard's administrative system for processing persons under
restricted legal categories during the Violet Compact era. It assigned classified names to
individuals—persons whose original identities were sealed for administrative purposes—and routed
them through the "resettled south" mechanism to southern frontier settlements, specifically
Rakuen. The apparatus operated at the intersection of several institutional functions: the
Sealed Names classified individuals and suppressed their original identities; the Bell Synod's
satellite witnessing office in Rakuen absorbed and eliminated testimonies from those individuals
that could embarrass the Violet Compact administration; and Midgaard's sealed warrant archive
provided the originating legal authority for the classifications. The apparatus was designed
using welfare-language framing—persons were classified as "resettled" for welfare purposes,
routing them under administrative categories that created documentation obligations without
creating welfare provision obligations. The apparatus is still partially operational within
Midgaard's Continuity faction: active sealed names classifications continue to run through
the same administrative pathways, though the volume is significantly lower than during the
Violet Compact peak period. Rakuen's Garden Ledger holds the most complete surviving external
evidence of the apparatus's operational scope.

flags MIDGAARD
---
The apparatus sits at the center of Midgaard's Continuity/Reckoning factional divide.
Continuity position: the apparatus was a legitimate emergency administrative tool; classifications were issued under valid authority; records are properly sealed under that authority.
Review requires demonstrating specific harm to a specifically identified party, which is structurally difficult when the identities of the classified persons are the thing that is sealed.
Reckoning position: the apparatus was designed to make its own accountability impossible — seal the names, disappear the testimonies, require identification of sealed persons as a precondition for reviewing why they were sealed.
The circular dependency is not accidental.
Midgaard's charter office currently holds approximately fourteen hundred active sealed classifications under Violet Compact-era authority.
The Continuity faction controls access to the review process; the Reckoning faction controls public advocacy but not the archive.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Black Ledger sits in direct institutional parallel to Midgaard's Sealed Names apparatus: both are sealed archive systems covering the condemned-debtor transfer operations of the Spirebound Conclave era.
Kowloon's Black Ledger covers delta settlement operations; the Sealed Names apparatus covers the upstream classification and routing mechanism.
If the Black Ledger were opened, the most useful cross-reference would be the Sealed Names apparatus classifications — the upstream records establishing which classified persons were routed where.
Both cities' Continuity factions have the same interest: neither archive opens until the other does, because each opening requires the other as context.
This perverse solidarity — shared guilt creating shared interest in sealed records — is the structural reason both archives remain closed.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's founding charter anti-sealed-warrant clause was written in direct response to the Sealed Names apparatus model.
The clause's specific language targets exactly the apparatus's operational mechanism: sealed classifications issued by a superior administrative authority that bind the classified person without their knowledge or ability to contest.
The Syndic Council maintains a formal opinion that Sealed Names classifications applied to persons who subsequently became Kiess residents are null and void under the charter's anti-sealed-warrant provision.
This opinion has not been tested in formal proceedings because no Sealed Names classified person has yet presented themselves to Kiess seeking that nullification.
The Syndic Council considers the opinion standing law; Midgaard's Continuity faction considers it an unauthorized nullification of valid sealed authority. The disagreement is formally active and unresolved.

flags RAKUEN
---
Rakuen's Garden Ledger is the most complete surviving external evidence of the Sealed Names apparatus's operational scope.
The Ledger Clerks have identified three categories of Violet Compact-era entries corresponding to apparatus operations: persons registered under sealed names without prior welfare classification documents, persons whose welfare classification documents were issued simultaneously with their registration, and persons whose welfare documentation references administrative routing categories not corresponding to any locatable welfare program.
These three categories together represent approximately four hundred and twenty persons in the Ledger's Violet Compact-era records.
The Clerks have matched approximately ninety of these persons to Bell Synod witnessing office intake records through cross-reference.
Both Reckoning faction attempts to use the Garden Ledger evidence to initiate formal review were denied on grounds that the Garden Ledger's classification has not been verified by cross-reference to the sealed apparatus records.

flags MAFDET
---
Mafdet's Ledger Houses encounter the Sealed Names apparatus when maritime estate claims reference persons classified under sealed names whose current legal status is unclear.
The most common scenario: an individual arrives in Mafdet with documents indicating a sealed-name classification and seeks to establish their original identity for property or inheritance purposes.
The Swift Court's position: the classification is acknowledged as having been issued by a competent authority, but its current effect under Strandline Compact jurisdiction requires independent assessment.
Mafdet has processed eleven such cases in the last thirty years; in seven, the claimant produced sufficient corroborating evidence to establish identity independent of the sealed classification; in four, the claim was suspended pending resolution of the classification's legal status.

flags MIDGAARD KHENARI
---
Khenari mortuary jurisprudence treats the Sealed Names apparatus as the most serious category of institutional harm: the administrative destruction of a living person's legal name prevents correct identification at the threshold of death.
If a person dies under a sealed name rather than their true name, the death record is incorrect, the inheritance chain is disrupted, and the debt-settlement process fails.
The nine descent families maintain a specific legal process for name restoration after institutional classification: it requires presentation of evidence to a Khenari mortuary tribunal and, if successful, produces a formal Name Restoration Certificate superseding sealed classifications in Khenari-governed legal proceedings.
Khenari archivists have issued seven Name Restoration Certificates for persons whose Sealed Names apparatus classifications were reconstructed through Garden Ledger cross-reference.

flags MIDGAARD UMBRAL
---
Umbral shadow-archives contain the largest collection of observation records relating to the Sealed Names apparatus's operational period.
Umbral communities near the Gloamvault site observed the intake and routing of classified persons through Kel'Shadra's institutional framework, maintaining records of who was observed entering, what documentation was presented, and who was not subsequently observed leaving.
The intake shadow for Sealed Names apparatus operations is documented in Umbral records as a specific operational pattern: persons arriving with welfare classification documents were typically observed entering and not observed exiting through standard channels.
Umbral archives cross-referenced with Garden Ledger entries have produced the most complete picture of the apparatus's downstream operation.
The Reckoning faction has formally requested access to Umbral observation records for the Violet Compact period; the Umbral archivist community has agreed to provide access subject to their own verification of the requesting parties' purposes.

flags RAKUEN KHENARI
---
Khenari archivists have been the most effective external researchers on the Sealed Names apparatus because their mortuary jurisprudence gives them a specific methodology for reconstructing classified names through death records.
If a person died in Rakuen during the Violet Compact era and was registered under a sealed name, the death record exists in Rakuen's registry under that name.
If the same person's original identity can be established through other records — family testimony, prior caravan registrations, Khenari mortuary records from their community of origin — the two records can be cross-referenced to establish that the sealed name and the original name refer to the same person.
This methodology has successfully matched forty-three Sealed Names apparatus classifications to original identities in the Garden Ledger reconstruction project.
The matches constitute the most concrete evidence currently available of what the apparatus was actually used for.
